  • Calculate a quantile regression

General Linear Regression

  • We can generalize the ordinary linear model to a more flexible framework
  • In regular regression, the predictor variables are on the same scale as the outcome.
  • This is often written out in the following form:

\[ E(Y) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k} + e \]

  • We could also write out this model using the distribution and matrix notation.
  • We are assuming the \(E(Y)\) follows a normal distribution, with a linear combination of predictors defining the mean, and the variance defined by \(sigma\).

\[ E(Y) \sim \text{Normal}(\mathbf X \beta,\sigma^2) \]

  • A more general framework would be to allow some function to link the predictors to the outcome, and allow different distributions other than the Normal distribution.
  • We call this function the ‘link function’.In normal regression it is simply the identity function.
  • We can also consider different distributional families for the outcome
  • The combination of the link function and the distributional family is the general linear model.

Quantile Regression

Although it would be reasonable to use linear regression in this problem, we may decide to implement quantile regression if we desire to make inference on the median, or perhaps the 75 percentile, rather than the mean. In that case, we must use quantile regression. Quantile regression works very similarly to linear regression in practice using Python, however, the underlying optimization is different. We will make inference on the 75 percentile for this exercise, but you could choose any percentile.

sales_subset[,quantile(sale_amount,0.75)]
##      75% 
## 582.1884

Quantile Regression

The interface for quantile regression uses the familiar R formula interface. We can set the tau or quantile to fit.

A null model recovers the quantile as calculated.

Note thaat if no quantile is specified the default median is used.

library(quantreg)
fit0 <- rq(sale_amount ~ 1,tau=0.75,data=sales_subset)
summary(fit0)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = sale_amount ~ 1, tau = 0.75, data = sales_subset)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.75
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Value     Std. Error t value   Pr(>|t|) 
## (Intercept) 582.18840   7.62030   76.39962   0.00000

Age by Sale Amount

We can investigate the relationship between age and the 75 percentile of sale amount. If we simply include age in the model as a linear predictor, we are assuming a linear relationship between these variables. Is that appropriate here?

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(sales_subset,
       aes(age,sale_amount)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method='lm') + 
  theme_minimal()

It looks like there is a non-linear relationship between age and the sale amount. In this case, we may be able to approximate it using a more flexible curve like this:

ggplot(sales_subset,aes(age,sale_amount))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method='loess')+theme_minimal()

Age by Sale Amount with a Polynomial Term

This looks like a good fit to the data. We can fit this in the linear model like so:

fit1 <- rq(sale_amount ~ age + I(age^2),tau=0.75,data=sales_subset)
summary(fit1)

Non-Linearity: Marketing Exposure

We may also be interested in estimating the effect of marketing exposure on the sale amount. Let’s begin by visualizing the relationship between these variables alone:

ggplot(sales_subset,aes(marketing_exposure,sale_amount))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method='lm')+theme_minimal()

It looks like there is an overall negative effect of marketing exposure! The more marketing exposure someone recieves, the less likely they are to buy the product?!? We will find this is not the case in the end, but let’s continue with this pairwise investigation for now. We can further examine this relationship by looking at a non-linear fit for this data.

ggplot(sales_subset,aes(marketing_exposure,sale_amount))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method='loess')+theme_minimal()

The non-linear fit gives us a similar answer as the linear fit. We can fit a flexible line in the context of regression by using splines. The general idea is that we split the data up into regions, then fit a polynomial within each region that connects. It is pretty straightforward to fit a spline model using the formula interface, but the output can be difficult to understand. We need to define the number of knots (the place we will split into different regions). Or we can define the degress of freedom.

fit3 <- rq(sale_amount ~ marketing_exposure,tau=0.75,data=sales_subset)
summary(fit3)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = sale_amount ~ marketing_exposure, tau = 0.75, data = sales_subset)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.75
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    Value     Std. Error t value   Pr(>|t|) 
## (Intercept)        721.33972  15.29833   47.15152   0.00000
## marketing_exposure -29.72276   2.46287  -12.06833   0.00000
fit4 <- rq(sale_amount ~ splines::bs(marketing_exposure,df=3),tau=0.75,data=sales_subset)
summary(fit4)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = sale_amount ~ splines::bs(marketing_exposure, df = 3), 
##     tau = 0.75, data = sales_subset)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.75
##

Mean vs Median

  • Median data is often considered more robust to outliers
  • Consider the difference between the mean fit (the red line)
  • To the median fit (the blue dotted line)
fit_mean <- lm(Sales~TV,data=ads)
fit_median <- rq(Sales~TV,data=ads) #default tau is .5
with(ads,plot(TV,Sales))
abline(fit_mean,col="red")
abline(fit_median,col="blue",lty=2)

Calculating Multiple Quantile Regressions

  • We can specify multiple quantiles, and regress on those in one step
  • We can use the coefficients in a visualization

Plotting Multiple Quantile Regressions

  • Calling plot() on the mutliple reqressions visualizes and summarizes the values of the coefficients.
plot(fitqs)

More Multiple Quantile Regressions

  • Alternatively, the rq command will allow us to search the full quantile space for the data with the tau = -1 option.
  • It turns out there are a finite number of solutions.
  • We can plot the solutions.
    • In this example, this demonstrates that what is happening at the lower end of the distribution (the smaller quantiles, tau<0.2) is not the same as beyond this point.
    • This can indicate that the extremes (upper or lower quantiles) behave differently than the center of the distribution
    • Ordinary least squares which estimates the mean response, would not necessarily pick up this level of detail
z<- rq(Sales~TV,tau = -1,data=ads)
#z #this produces a lot of output! Uncomment to inspect
#z$sol # this is the "primal solution"
plot(z)

Quantreg Details Methods

  • The default calculation method for the quantile regression here is called the “br” method (Barrodale and Roberts algorithm)
  • This is recommended for “medium” size problems, but for larger problems, there is a choice of other fitting methods. In the documentation, the next “step up” is the “fn” (Frisch-Newton interior point) method.
  • If you are trying to compute quantile regression on larger datasets or larger sets of parameters, consult the documentation. Several alternative computational methods (solvers) are provided.
fit_default <- rq(Sales~TV,tau=0.5,data=ads)
summary(fit_default)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = Sales ~ TV, tau = 0.5, data = ads)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.5
## 
## Coefficients:
##             coefficients lower bd upper bd
## (Intercept) 6.52911      5.74645  7.16360 
## TV          0.05063      0.04704  0.05469
#
fit_alt <- rq(Sales~TV,tau=0.5,data=ads, method="fn")
summary(fit_alt)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = Sales ~ TV, tau = 0.5, data = ads, method = "fn")
## 
## tau: [1] 0.5
## 
## Coefficients:
##             coefficients lower bd upper bd
## (Intercept) 6.52911      5.74645  7.16360 
## TV          0.05063      0.04704  0.05469
#in this case it won't make much difference

Quantreg Details Standard Errors

  • Additionally, there are alternative methods for calculating the standard errors
  • The default method is slow for data set sizes over 1000 observations
  • We show here the bootstrap alternative, but again check the documents for others and details (there are 7 different methods provided!)
fit_default <- rq(Sales~TV,tau=0.5,data=ads)
summary(fit_default)
## 
## Call: rq(formula = Sales ~ TV, tau = 0.5, data = ads)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.5
## 
## Coefficients:
##             coefficients lower bd upper bd
## (Intercept) 6.52911      5.74645  7.16360 
## TV          0.05063      0.04704  0.05469
summary(fit_default,se="boot")
## 
## Call: rq(formula = Sales ~ TV, tau = 0.5, data = ads)
## 
## tau: [1] 0.5
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Value    Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  6.52911  0.44290   14.74172  0.00000
## TV           0.05063  0.00323   15.65382  0.00000

Conclusion

  • Quantile regression is easy to implement in R
  • Computationally it can be more costly
  • Uses the familiar formula interface
  • Robust to outliers
